04919nam a22006375i 9780674269613DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742696137 a10.4159/97806742696132doi  a(DE-B1597)590534  a(OCoLC)1267767012  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBX1528b.S56 2021 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a261.70944/09042231 aShortall, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSoldiers of God in a Secular World :bCatholic Theology and Twentieth-Century French Politics /cSarah Shortall. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: SEPARATION (1880 –1939) -- t1. Exile Catholicism -- t2. From Royalism to the Mystical Body of Christ -- tPART II: RESISTANCE (1940 –1944) -- t3. Fighting Nazism with the “Weapons of the Spirit” -- t4. The Theoretical Foundations of the Spiritual Resistance -- tPART III: RENEWAL (1945–1965) -- t5. The Postwar Catholic Engagement with the Left -- t6. The Drama of Atheist Humanism and the Politics of History -- t7. The Death and Resurrection of the Nouvelle Théologie -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA revelatory account of the nouvelle théologie, a clerical movement that revitalized the Catholic Church’s role in twentieth-century French political life. Secularism has been a cornerstone of French political culture since 1905, when the republic formalized the separation of church and state. At times the barrier of secularism has seemed impenetrable, stifling religious actors wishing to take part in political life. Yet in other instances, secularism has actually nurtured movements of the faithful. Soldiers of God in a Secular World explores one such case, that of the nouvelle théologie, or new theology. Developed in the interwar years by Jesuits and Dominicans, the nouvelle théologie reimagined the Church’s relationship to public life, encouraging political activism, engaging with secular philosophy, and inspiring doctrinal changes adopted by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s. Nouveaux théologiens charted a path between the old alliance of throne and altar and secularism’s demand for the privatization of religion. Envisioning a Church in but not of the public sphere, Catholic thinkers drew on theological principles to intervene in political questions while claiming to remain at arm’s length from politics proper. Sarah Shortall argues that this “counter-politics” was central to the mission of the nouveaux théologiens: by recoding political statements in the ostensibly apolitical language of doctrine, priests were able to enter into debates over fascism and communism, democracy and human rights, colonialism and nuclear war. This approach found its highest expression during the Second World War, when the nouveaux théologiens led the spiritual resistance against Nazism. Claiming a powerful public voice, they collectively forged a new role for the Church amid the momentous political shifts of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aChurch and statezFrancexCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20th century. 0aNouvelle théologie (Catholic theology)zFrance. 0aSecularismxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269613/original  a978-